{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/lipid-modification-cvd-prevention/background-information/lipids-cardiovascular-health/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"f4e4cb23-7f1d-5543-a7a5-9316a25c589b","slug":"lipids-cardiovascular-health","fullItemName":"Lipids and cardiovascular health","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 63d314b0-2cac-4d33-8313-a322df86e2df --><h2>What is the relationship between blood lipids and cardiovascular health?</h2><!-- end field 63d314b0-2cac-4d33-8313-a322df86e2df -->","summary":"","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item cf434916-a293-4d2e-a79d-b8a9830ba0de --><!-- begin field c333f6e8-9ffb-46db-9f08-f25f7fb714a5 --><ul><li>Cardiovascular disease (CVD) is an umbrella term that describes a range of conditions that affect the heart, the blood vessels, or both. It is caused by blood clots (thrombosis), or atherosclerosis.</li><li>Atherosclerosis is a condition where there is a build up of fatty deposits (plaques) inside an artery that cause the artery to harden and narrow, restricting blood flow. <ul><li>Cardiovascular conditions caused by atherosclerosis include: <ul><li>Coronary heart disease (including angina and myocardial infarction).</li><li>Stroke.</li><li>Transient ischaemic attack (TIA).</li><li>Peripheral arterial disease.</li></ul></li></ul></li><li><strong>The risk of CVD can be reduced by modification of the blood lipid profile </strong>(as well as other modifiable risk factors, such as lifestyle measures). <ul><li>Total cholesterol is an important predictor of CVD events. However, non-high density lipoprotein cholesterol (non-HDL-C), the difference between total and HDL cholesterol, which usually makes up 60–70% of total serum cholesterol is a powerful risk factor. </li><li>Non-HDL-C has replaced low density lipoprotein cholesterol (LDL-C) as the primary target for reducing cardiovascular (CV) risk with lipid modifying treatment.</li><li>HDL-C is inversely related to CV risk. </li><li>Elevated triglyceride levels (greater than 2.3 mmol/L), especially when HDL-C levels are low, is a risk factor for CVD and is independent of total cholesterol.<ul><li>Extreme levels of triglycerides (greater than 20 mmol/L) are associated with pancreatitis and a high risk of morbidity and mortality. </li></ul></li></ul></li><li>Blood lipids are only one of many important risk factors associated with the development of CVD.<ul><li>For further information on CVD risk factors, and risk assessment and modification, see the section on <a class=\"topic-reference external-reference\" href=\"/topics/cvd-risk-assessment-management/background-information/risk-factors-for-cvd/\">Risk factors for CVD</a> in the CKS topic on <a class=\"topic-reference external-reference\" href=\"/topics/cvd-risk-assessment-management/\">CVD risk assessment and management</a>.</li></ul></li></ul><p>[<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/lipid-modification-cvd-prevention/references/\">JBS3 Board, 2014</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/lipid-modification-cvd-prevention/references/\">NICE, 2016a</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/lipid-modification-cvd-prevention/references/\">SIGN, 2017</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/lipid-modification-cvd-prevention/references/\">BMJ, 2018</a>]</p><!-- end field c333f6e8-9ffb-46db-9f08-f25f7fb714a5 --><!-- end item cf434916-a293-4d2e-a79d-b8a9830ba0de -->","topic":{"id":"5303951d-71d9-506d-84ec-cbdd7ff3b93e","topicId":"dc4f1ad8-1fac-4248-9071-a622ca58dd2c","topicName":"Lipid modification - CVD prevention","slug":"lipid-modification-cvd-prevention","lastRevised":"Last revised in October 2020","chapters":[{"id":"7834a360-a716-55db-beef-e74397381f6b","fullItemName":"Summary","slug":"summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"4149ed5c-ad54-5793-8860-4b2f82d94427","fullItemName":"Have I got the 